The independence referendum pushed up rents across Scotland to an all-time high, property experts have said. Referendum pushed up rent prices The independence referendum pushed up rents across Scotland to an all-time high, property experts have said.Uncertainty over the outcome of the vote led to a growth in the sector as cautious potential property owners delayed purchases and turned to renting as a stop-gap, according to the latest Scotland Buy-to-Let Index from Your Move.The lettings agent found the average Scottish rent now stands at &pound;537 a month, a &pound;14 (2.7%) increase in the year to August.Rents have risen across Scotland with new records set in Edinburgh and Glasgow at &pound;602 and &pound;575 respectively.The growth in the sector accelerated as polling day approached, with average residential rents rising 1.3% in the three months to August. 